# My Black Counts Mini-Experiment
# Outreach Experiment in Alameda County and LA County
# Step 2: Exploratory analysis of the data.
options(scipen=999999)

# Because this is in an R Project, the working directory paths are relative, not fixed

# loads the PostgreSQL driver
drv <- dbDriver("PostgreSQL")

# create connection to db 
con <- dbConnect(drv, dbname = "census_2020",
                 host = "aws-postgres-db.c5udgz7ro8hq.us-west-2.rds.amazonaws.com", port = 5432,
                 user = "postgres", password = "password")

dat <- st_read(con, query = "SELECT * FROM mbc_experiment_zip_0720_0726")

1. Define Question

Primary question:

  • Did treatment zip codes have larger response rate gains than control zip codes?

Secondary questions:

  • Are there any variables correlated with higher response rate gains?

  • Are there differences by county (Alameda vs. Los Angeles)?

  • Are there additional contextual factors to consider?

    • E.g. phone banking outreach from MBC

2. Exploratory Analysis

Explore experiment data

  • No clear trends re: county or treatment group vs. quartile of response rate increase.

Graph the start/end in response rates by treatment group.

datlong <- 
dat %>% 
  select(zip, county_name, exp_flag, resp_start, resp_end) %>% 
  pivot_longer(-c(zip, county_name, exp_flag), names_to = "date", values_to = "resp") %>% 
  mutate(date = factor(date, ordered=TRUE, 
                       levels = c("resp_start", "resp_end")))



ggplot(datlong, aes(x=date, y=resp, group=zip, color=county_name)) +
  geom_line()+
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~exp_flag) +
  labs(title="Start and End Response Rates",
       subtitle = "By Treatment Group")

Distribution of Response Rate Gains

  • The distribution of response rate gains for the control group is wider and ranges higher. More variability both low and high. Group means seem nearly equal, with the control group slightly higher.

  • The distribution of response rate gains for the treatment group has a smaller range, with a top range that is a little lower than the control group.

dat %>% 
  select(zip, county_name, exp_flag, resp_diff) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(exp_flag, resp_diff)) +
  geom_boxplot(varwidth = T, fill="plum") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Response Rate Gains",
       subtitle="by Treatment Group")

Distribution by group and county

  • When the data is broken up by county, we see that there is way more variation in Alameda county than in Los Angeles.

  • In both counties the control group has a slightly higher mean than the treatment group.

  • In LA the treatment group varies more but the variation ranges lower than the control–top range of both are about the same.

  • In Alameda county the bulk of the treatment group ranges slightly higher than the control group, and the bottom range is slightly higher as well.

library(ggcorrplot)

# prep data for correlation

datcor_treatment <- 
  dat %>% 
  filter(exp_flag=="treatment") %>% 
  select(blackhh_prc,resp_diff , results, reach, impressions, link_clicks,
         unique_link_clicks, amount_spent_usd, cost_per_results, contacts)


# create correlation matrix
treatment_corr <- round(cor(datcor_treatment), 1)
# save p values in case
p.mat <- cor_pmat(treatment_corr)

# test correlation
ggcorrplot(treatment_corr, hc.order = TRUE,
    p.mat = p.mat, sig.level = 0.05)

  • In the correlation matric I see that the response rate gain has some positive correlation with key outreach metrics, but none of the correlations are statistically significant (at p < 0.5).

    • They are significant at p < 0.1, but, that’s not particularly significant.

Review correlation of (non outreach) independent variables

datcor <- 
  dat %>% 
 # filter(exp_flag=="treatment") %>% 
  select(estimate, blackhh_prc, foreign.born, internet, multiunit, poverty, renter, count_tract,

# create correlation matrix

# test correlation
ggcorrplot(corr, hc.order = TRUE, type = "lower",
   lab = TRUE)

  • Poverty rate is strongly correlated with the mean Black HTC score and lack of internet, not surprisingly.

  • I’ll check the collinearity of variables later.

Plot linear regression

  • Quick plot of dependent variable (response rate difference) against outreach metrics, including treatment and control zips.

  • Without disaggregating by county, we see a moderate positive linear relationship between clicks and response rate gain, although the confidence interval is pretty big.

ggplot(dat, aes(x=clicks_all, y=resp_diff)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=mean_blkhtc_num), size=3) +
  scale_color_gradient(low="blue", high="red")+
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  labs(title="All Clicks by Response Rate Gain: Treatment + Control")

  • When I disaggregate by county we see pretty drastic differences between LA County and Alameda County. Alameda county shows a fairly strong linear relationship though a very large confidence interval (similar to boxplots above), while the LA County plot shows very slight positive relationship, though the line is mostly level.

  • This tells me I should consider handling the counties separately, or a multilevel model.

ggplot(dat, aes(x=clicks_all, y=resp_diff)) +
    geom_point(aes(color=mean_blkhtc_num), size=3) +
  scale_color_gradient(low="blue", high="red")+
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
    facet_wrap(~county_name) +
  labs(title="All Clicks by Response Rate Gain: Treatment + Control", subtitle="by county")

  • Just looking at treatment zips, the linear relationship in LA is stronger but both counties have large variation bands/confidence interval.

3. Model Testing

  • dependent variable: response rate gain

  • independent variables: demographics, outreach, treatment group

  • Separate counties (also try together)

4. Answer Questions

Primary question:

  • Did treatment zip codes have larger response rate gains than control zip codes?

    • Overall, there is a slight trend of more clicks corresponding with higher response rate difference, but it is not a clear trend and the confidence intervals are large.

    • No statistically significant trends showing

Secondary questions:

  • Are there any variables correlated with higher response rate gains?

    • Looking at the correlation plot, none of the independent variables are correlated strongly with the response rate gain. The percent of Black households is slightly negatively correlated (-0.3) with response rate gain, but that is the strongest correlation.

    • Interestingly there is also no correlation (correlation = 0) between response rate and response rate gain–meaning that whether an area is high- or low-responding doesn’t necessarily correlate to whether the area was more likely to gain responses during this experiment.

  • Are there differences by county (Alameda vs. Los Angeles)?

    • Yes, Alameda County shows huge variation by zip codes but also a generally stronger trend between response rate gains and outreach.

  • Are there additional contextual factors to consider? E.g. phone banking outreach from MBC

    • The phone banking outreach doesn’t correlate with response rate gains. The independent variables lack of internet access and poverty rate are the 2 that are the best explanatory varibles, both better at explaining variation in zip code response rate gain than the outreach metrics.
